04773nam a22007095i 9780292796256DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212006txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927962567 a10.7560/7097132doi  a(DE-B1597)587614  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aPS153.L46bE85 2006 7aLIT0040502bisacsh04a810.992066432221 aEsquibel, Catrióna Rueda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWith Her Machete in Her Hand :bReading Chicana Lesbians /cCatrióna Rueda Esquibel. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue: A Chicana Lesbian Scholar’s Tale -- tIntroduction: History -- tCHAPTER 1 Chicana Lesbian Fictions -- tCHAPTER 2 The Mystery of the Weeping Woman -- tCHAPTER 3 Black Velvet Fantasies: “The” Aztec Princess in the Chicana/o Sexual Imagination -- tCHAPTER 4 Sor Juana and the Search for (Queer) Cultural Heroes -- tCHAPTER 5 Memories of Girlhood: Chicana Lesbian Fictions -- tCHAPTER 6 Shameless Histories: Talking Race/Talking Sex -- tCHAPTER 7 Queer for the Revolution: The Representation of Politics and the Politics of Representation -- tCHAPTER 8 Conclusion: With Her Machete in Her Hand -- tAPPENDIX Toward a Chronological Bibliography of Chicana Lesbian Fictions, 1971–2000 -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the 1981 publication of the groundbreaking anthology This Bridge Called My Back: Writings by Radical Women of Color, Cherríe Moraga and Gloria Anzaldúa ushered in an era of Chicana lesbian writing. But while these two writers have achieved iconic status, observers of the Chicana/o experience have been slow to perceive the existence of a whole community—lesbian and straight, male as well as female—who write about the Chicana lesbian experience. To create a first full map of that community, this book explores a wide range of plays, novels, and short stories by Chicana/o authors that depict lesbian characters or lesbian desire. Catrióna Rueda Esquibel starts from the premise that Chicana/o communities, theories, and feminisms cannot be fully understood without taking account of the perspectives and experiences of Chicana lesbians. To open up these perspectives, she engages in close readings of works centered around the following themes: La Llorona, the Aztec Princess, Sor Juana Inés de la Cruz, girlhood friendships, rural communities and history, and Chicana activism. Her investigation broadens the community of Chicana lesbian writers well beyond Moraga and Anzaldúa, while it also demonstrates that the histories of Chicana lesbians have had to be written in works of fiction because these women have been marginalized and excluded in canonical writings on Chicano life and experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAmerican literaturexMexican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexWomen authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aLesbians in literature. 0aLesbians' writings, AmericanxHistory and criticism. 0aMexican American lesbiansxIntellectual life. 0aMexican American women in literature. 0aMexican American womenxIntellectual life. 0aMexican Americans in literature. 0aWomen and literaturezUnited States. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / Hispanic American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70971340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796256423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796256/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyt